==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Conjoint
<hw>Con*joint"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>conjoint</ets>, p. p. of <ets>conjoindre</ets>. See
<er>Conjoin</er>, and cf. <er>Conjunct</er>.]</ety> <def>United;
connected; associated.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Influence
<xex>conjoint</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Glover.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Conjoint degrees</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>two
notes which follow each other immediately in the order of the scale, as
<xex>ut</xex> and <xex>re</xex>.</cd> <au>Johnson.</au> --
<col><b>Conjoint tetrachords</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>two
tetrachords or fourths, where the same note is the highest of one and
the lowest of the other; -- also written
<asp>conjunct</asp>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Conjointly</ent>⟦br⟧
